On Friday, Apple and Google announced an unprecedented project to track and halt the spread of the novel coronavirus — and we haven’t stopped talking about it since.
It’s been messy, but a lot of the major questions have been answered, although there’s one lingering one that hasn’t.
The system does a good job keeping data local and anonymized, although it gets less private if you share your diagnosis.
That leads to the one big question we still can’t answer: are public health organizations actually going to use this?
How those agencies respond — whether they adopt the new system or ignore it — is the single most important question for whether the plan moves forward.